{"title_page": "Tulasa Thapa", "text_new": "{{short description|Sex worker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Tulasa Thapa\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = 1970\n| birth_place = [[Thankot]], [[Nepal]]\n| death_date = 1995\n| death_place =\n| death_cause = [[Tuberculosis]]\n| residence =\n| nationality = [[Nepal]]i\n| other_names =\n| known_for =\n| education =\n| employer =\n| occupation = \n| title =\n| spouse =\n| parents =\n| relatives =\n}}\n\n'''Tulasa Thapa''' (1970\u20131995) was a [[Nepal]]i girl who was [[kidnap]]ped from her home village of [[Thankot]] near [[Kathmandu]] in 1982 at the age of 13,<ref name=\"indiatoday\">{{cite web|last1=Singh|first1=Chander Uday|title=13-year-old girl from Nepal suffers the horrors of Bombay's flesh markets|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/19821231-13-year-old-girl-from-nepal-suffers-the-horrors-of-bombay-flesh-markets-772499-2013-07-26|website=India Today|accessdate=11 April 2018|language=en|date=July 26, 2013}}</ref> smuggled into [[Mumbai]] via the border town of [[Birganj]] in [[Parsa District]], and sold into [[Prostitution in India|prostitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://db.jhuccp.org/ics-wpd/exec/icswppro.dll?BU=http://db.jhuccp.org/ics-wpd/exec/icswppro.dll&QF0=DocNo&QI0=289860&TN=Popline&AC=QBE_QUERY&MR=30%25&nbsp;DL=1&&RL=1&&RF=LongRecordDisplay&DF=LongRecordDisplay|title=Tulasa and the horrors of child prostitution sold and resold body and soul.}}</ref> She was systematically beaten into submission, then repeatedly [[rape]]d to make her fit for the trade. She was sold to three different brothels in Mumbai, at prices ranging from 5000 to 7000 [[rupee]]s.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} In addition to the sex work she was forced to do in the [[brothel]] at a minimum of three customers per night (with an average of eight), she was sent to various city hotels dressed in European style clothes to entertain customers for 180 rupees per night until at last a hotel manager reported her to the police.{{Citation needed|date=April 2008}} Following the public outcry, the governments of India and Nepal signed a 1985 cooperation agreement addressing the rescue and repatriation of Nepali girls trafficked into brothels in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beacononline.wordpress.com/2008/09/07/rape-for-profit-trafficking-of-nepali-girls-and-women-to-indias-brothels/|title=Trafficking of Nepali Girls and Women to India\u2019s Brothels}}</ref>\n\n== Rescue ==\nTen months later, in November 1982, when she was brought to Bombay's [[Grant Medical College and Sir Jamshedjee Jeejebhoy Group of Hospitals|JJ Hospital]], she was suffering from three types of [[sexually transmitted disease]]s, [[genital warts]] and brain [[tuberculosis]] which left her [[Spasticity|spastic]] and permanently using, and finally led to her death.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} The People's Health Organisation embarked on a full-fledged \"Save Tulasa\" campaign, and with the support of the media managed to rescue her. At the hospital, Tulasa was given police protection against possible reprisals from the prostitution industry. After a period of stay in the [[Dongri Remand Home]], she returned to Nepal to take up residence in the [[Cheshire Home For the Disabled]] in [[Jorpati]]. Doctors evaluated Tulasa and found her to be severely damaged physically and psychologically.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} Over the years, she remained incoherent and rambling in her speech. She used a wheelchair full-time and complained that her stomach hurt all the time, and that she could not go to the toilet.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} Attempts were made to return her to her father, Bir Dhoj Thapa, but she was rejected by his second wife (Tulasa's mother had died shortly after her abduction), and eventually her family stopped visiting her. In 1994 Tulasa broke her leg in a [[suicide]] attempt.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}\n\n== Death and media outcry ==\nShe was released from her institution in 1995, seemingly cured, but had a relapse and died that same year at age 24{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} of the tuberculosis she had acquired while enslaved as a [[sex worker]] in [[India]].\n\nThe resulting media outcry resulted in the governments of India and Nepal signing a treaty for the rescue and repatriation of Nepali girls from Indian brothels.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}} In India the sentence for trafficking with minors has been hiked from 7 years to 13. [[Child prostitution]] has been reduced by about 40% but remains a major problem and no accurate figures are available. According to [[Reuters]] (Masako Iijima, \"S. Asia Urged to Unite Against Child Prostitution,\" Reuters, June 19, 1998), over 40% of 484 prostituted girls rescued during major raids of brothels in Bombay in 1996 were from Nepal.\n\nIn 2000, she was back in the news for a short time as the verdict was delivered in the case against her persecutors. In the first report recorded on December 6, 1982, Tulasa had named 32 people responsible for abducting her and selling her to different brothels. These included taximen, the abductors and the brothel-owners. She also named three other Nepali men, Kancha Sarkhi, Lal Bahadur Kani and Uttam Kumar Pariyar{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}, whom the Nepal government had arrested and finally sentenced to 20 years' imprisonment. Out of the 32 people arrested by Bombay police, seven were charged but released due to a lack of evidence. Only one of the nine suspects faced trial, the rest having hidden themselves away. The single accused was released by the judge on grounds of inadequate evidence.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links and references==\n* [http://www.sharonmaas.com/child-prostitution-in-india Saving Tulasa, Child Sex Worker from India ]\n* [http://freespirit.members.gn.apc.org/victims.htm ''Victims of the Dar'' from '''The Hindu Online''', September 29, 1996]\n* [http://208.184.138.109/news/2000/jan/24tulasa.htm ''The shade of Tulasa seeks justice'' by Kanchana Suggu]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n* Robert I. Freidman, \"India\u2019s Shame: Sexual Slavery and Political Corruption Are Leading to An AIDS Catastrophe,\" The Nation, 8 April 1996.\n\n{{Prostitution in India}}\n{{Social issues in India}}\n{{Sexual abuse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thapa, Tulasa}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kathmandu District]]\n[[Category:20th-century deaths from tuberculosis]]\n[[Category:Nepalese female prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Indian female prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Nepalese victims of crime]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in India]]\n[[Category:Sex crimes in India]]\n[[Category:Gang rape]]\n[[Category:Victims of forced prostitution]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sex worker}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Tulasa Thapa\n| image = \n| image_size = \n| caption =\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date = 1970\n| birth_place = [[Thankot]], [[Nepal]]\n| death_date = 1995\n| death_place =\n| death_cause = [[Tuberculosis]]\n| residence =\n| nationality = [[Nepal]]i\n| other_names =\n| known_for =\n| education =\n| employer =\n| occupation = \n| title =\n| spouse =\n| parents =\n| relatives =\n}}\n\n'''Tulasa Thapa''' (1970\u20131995) was a [[Nepal]]i girl who was [[kidnap]]ped from her home village of [[Thankot]] near [[Kathmandu]] in 1982 at the age of 13,<ref name=\"indiatoday\">{{cite web|last1=Singh|first1=Chander Uday|title=13-year-old girl from Nepal suffers the horrors of Bombay's flesh markets|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/indiascope/story/19821231-13-year-old-girl-from-nepal-suffers-the-horrors-of-bombay-flesh-markets-772499-2013-07-26|website=India Today|accessdate=11 April 2018|language=en|date=July 26, 2013}}</ref> smuggled into [[Mumbai]] via the border town of [[Birganj]] in [[Parsa District]], and sold into [[Prostitution in India|prostitution]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://db.jhuccp.org/ics-wpd/exec/icswppro.dll?BU=http://db.jhuccp.org/ics-wpd/exec/icswppro.dll&QF0=DocNo&QI0=289860&TN=Popline&AC=QBE_QUERY&MR=30%25&nbsp;DL=1&&RL=1&&RF=LongRecordDisplay&DF=LongRecordDisplay|title=Tulasa and the horrors of child prostitution sold and resold body and soul.}}</ref> She was systematically beaten into submission, then repeatedly [[rape]]d to make her fit for the trade. She was sold to three different brothels in Mumbai, at prices ranging from 5000 to 7000 [[rupee]]s.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} In addition to the sex work she was forced to do in the [[brothel]] at a minimum of three customers per night (with an average of eight), she was sent to various city hotels dressed in European style clothes to entertain customers for 180 rupees per night until at last a hotel manager reported her to the police.{{Citation needed|date=April 2008}} Following the public outcry, the governments of India and Nepal signed a 1985 cooperation agreement addressing the rescue and repatriation of Nepali girls trafficked into brothels in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beacononline.wordpress.com/2008/09/07/rape-for-profit-trafficking-of-nepali-girls-and-women-to-indias-brothels/|title=Trafficking of Nepali Girls and Women to India\u2019s Brothels}}</ref>\n\n== Rescue ==\nTen months later, in November 1982, when she was brought to Bombay's [[Grant Medical College and Sir Jamshedjee Jeejebhoy Group of Hospitals|JJ Hospital]], she was suffering from three types of [[sexually transmitted disease]]s, [[genital warts]] and brain [[tuberculosis]] which left her [[Spasticity|spastic]] and permanently using, and finally led to her death.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} The People\u2019s Health Organisation embarked on a full-fledged \"Save Tulasa\" campaign, and with the support of the media managed to rescue her. At the hospital, Tulasa was given police protection against possible reprisals from the prostitution industry. After a period of stay in the [[Dongri Remand Home]], she returned to Nepal to take up residence in the [[Cheshire Home For the Disabled]] in [[Jorpati]]. Doctors evaluated Tulasa and found her to be severely damaged physically and psychologically.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} Over the years, she remained incoherent and rambling in her speech. She used a wheelchair full-time and complained that her stomach hurt all the time, and that she could not go to the toilet.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} Attempts were made to return her to her father, Bir Dhoj Thapa, but she was rejected by his second wife (Tulasa's mother had died shortly after her abduction), and eventually her family stopped visiting her. In 1994 Tulasa broke her leg in a [[suicide]] attempt.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}\n\n== Death and media outcry ==\nShe was released from her institution in 1995, seemingly cured, but had a relapse and died that same year at age 24{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} of the tuberculosis she had acquired while enslaved as a [[sex worker]] in [[India]].\n\nThe resulting media outcry resulted in the governments of India and Nepal signing a treaty for the rescue and repatriation of Nepali girls from Indian brothels.{{Citation needed|date=January 2009}} In India the sentence for trafficking with minors has been hiked from 7 years to 13. [[Child prostitution]] has been reduced by about 40% but remains a major problem and no accurate figures are available. According to [[Reuters]] (Masako Iijima, \"S. Asia Urged to Unite Against Child Prostitution,\" Reuters, June 19, 1998), over 40% of 484 prostituted girls rescued during major raids of brothels in Bombay in 1996 were from Nepal.\n\nIn 2000, she was back in the news for a short time as the verdict was delivered in the case against her persecutors. In the first report recorded on December 6, 1982, Tulasa had named 32 people responsible for abducting her and selling her to different brothels. These included taximen, the abductors and the brothel-owners. She also named three other Nepali men, Kancha Sarkhi, Lal Bahadur Kani and Uttam Kumar Pariyar{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}, whom the Nepal government had arrested and finally sentenced to 20 years' imprisonment. Out of the 32 people arrested by Bombay police, seven were charged but released due to a lack of evidence. Only one of the nine suspects faced trial, the rest having hidden themselves away. The single accused was released by the judge on grounds of inadequate evidence.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links and references==\n* [http://www.sharonmaas.com/child-prostitution-in-india Saving Tulasa, Child Sex Worker from India ]\n* [http://freespirit.members.gn.apc.org/victims.htm ''Victims of the Dar'' from '''The Hindu Online''', September 29, 1996]\n* [http://208.184.138.109/news/2000/jan/24tulasa.htm ''The shade of Tulasa seeks justice'' by Kanchana Suggu]{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=no }}\n* Robert I. Freidman, \"India\u2019s Shame: Sexual Slavery and Political Corruption Are Leading to An AIDS Catastrophe,\" The Nation, 8 April 1996.\n\n{{Prostitution in India}}\n{{Social issues in India}}\n{{Sexual abuse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thapa, Tulasa}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:1995 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Kathmandu District]]\n[[Category:20th-century deaths from tuberculosis]]\n[[Category:Nepalese female prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Indian female prostitutes]]\n[[Category:Nepalese victims of crime]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Violence against women in India]]\n[[Category:Sex crimes in India]]\n[[Category:Gang rape]]\n[[Category:Victims of forced prostitution]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRescue:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tulasa_Thapa"}
{"title_page": "Nalini Jameela", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1954|08|18}}  \n| birth_place   = [[Kallur, Thrissur|Kallur village]], [[Thrissur]], [[India]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Indian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Prostitute]]<br>[[Sex work]] archivist<br>Author\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = Autobiography of a Sex Worker (2005)<br>Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker (2018)\n}}\n'''Nalini Jameela''' (born 18 August 1954) is an [[India]]n best selling author,<ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-12/20/content_504790.htm|title=Indian prostitute mum sparks storm with book|date=2005-12-20|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn}}</ref> [[sex worker]] activist and former [[prostitute]] from [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]]. She is the author of the books ''The Autobiography of a Sex-worker'' (2005) and ''Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker'' (2018). She is the coordinator of the ''Sex Workers Forum of Kerala'' (SWFK)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp|title=The life of the Silenced|last=Ittyipe|first=Minu S.|date=2005-07-30|publisher=[[Tehelka]]|accessdate=23 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130203204951/http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp|archivedate=3 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and is a member of the five [[NGO|non-governmental organisations]] (NGO).<ref name=\"actress\" />\n\n==Biography==\nNalini Jameela was born on 18 August 1954 in [[Kallur, Thrissur|Kallur village]], [[Thrissur]], India. She worked in the fields planting and harvesting crops <ref name=\"Scroll.in\">{{cite web |last1=Jameela |first1=Nalini |title=In a new book, Nalini Jameela breaks taboos and writes about her romantic encounters as a sex worker |url=https://scroll.in/article/878956/in-a-new-book-nalini-jameela-breaks-taboos-and-writes-about-her-romantic-encounters-as-a-sex-worker |website=Scroll.in |accessdate=10 March 2019 |date=16 May 2018}}</ref> until her husband died of [[cancer]] when she was aged 24.<ref name=\"scmp\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/509522/indian-prostitute-reveals-all-gripping-autobiography|title=Indian prostitute reveals all in gripping autobiography|last=|first=|date=25 July 2005|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=2018-05-16|language=en}}</ref> This left her with no means of supporting her two young children.<ref name=\"Tehelka\">{{cite web |last1=Ittyipe |first1=Minu |title=The life of the Silenced |url=http://tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp |website=Tehelka - The People's Paper |accessdate=10 March 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314112521/http://tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp |archivedate=14 March 2012 |date=14 March 2012}}</ref> A prostitute<ref name=\"scmp\" /> named Rosechechi introduced her to [[prostitution]]. Rosechechi arranged her first [[Client (prostitution)|client]], a senior police officer, and she met him in a guesthouse in Trissur that was frequented by politicians. When leaving the guesthouse in the morning she was arrested by the police and beaten.<ref name=\"Tehelka\" />\n\nShe had left school after the 3rd grade when she was about seven.<ref name=\"chinadaily\" /> In the 1990s she furthered her education at the Kallur Government School, eventually reaching the 12th grade.<ref name=\"puzha\" /> \n\nIn 2001 she became coordinator of the ''Sex Workers Forum of Kerala'' (SWFK),<ref name=\"puzha\">{{cite web |title=books.puzha.com - Author Details |url=http://www.puzha.com/malayalam/bookstore/cgi-bin/author-detail.cgi?code=2041 |website=www.puzha.com |accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref> Under her leadership the SWFK held protest marches to draw attention to the plight of [[Street prostitution|street-based]] sex workers.<ref name=\"Firstpost\">{{cite web |last1=Mitra |first1=Ipshita |title=Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker: Nalini Jameela returns, with eight new stories from her past |url=https://www.firstpost.com/living/romantic-encounters-of-a-sex-worker-nalini-jameela-returns-with-eight-new-stories-from-her-past-4433545.html |website=Firstpost |accessdate=10 March 2019 |date=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nJameela is a member of the five non-governmental organisations (NGO).<ref name=\"actress\">{{cite web |title=\u0d28\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d3f \u0d1c\u0d2e\u0d40\u0d32\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d06\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d15\u0d25 \u0d05\u0d2d\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d2a\u0d3e\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d |trans-title=Nalini Jameela's autobiography |url=https://malayalam.boldsky.com/insync/2006/102606jameela-now-an-actress.html |website=malayalam.boldsky.com |accessdate=10 March 2019 |language=ml |date=26 October 2006}}</ref> At the fourth meeting of the AIDS Counselling Program in [[Bangalore]], she called on the government not just to distribute [[condoms]], but to provide an education to sex workers and their children.<ref name=\"malayalam.webdunia\" />\n\n==Works==\n===Autobiography of a Sex Worker===\nIn 2005 Jameela wrote the autobiographical book ''Oru Lymgikathozhilaliyude Atmakatha''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jameela |first1=Nalini |title=Oru Lymgikathozhilaliyude Atmakatha |date=2010 |publisher=D C Books |isbn=9788126438105 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aemvDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=nalini+jameela#v=onepage&q=nalini%20jameela&f=false |language=ml |orig-year= 2005}}</ref> (Autobiography of a Sex Worker) with the aid of sex work activist I. Gopinath.<ref name=\"chinadaily\" /> The book sold 13,000 copies, ran to six editions within 100 days of publication.<ref name=\"The Indian Express\">{{cite web |last1=Pillai |first1=Pooja |title=How to Talk about Sex Without Offending People |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/how-to-talk-about-sex-without-offending-people-5110176/ |website=The Indian Express |accessdate=10 March 2019 |language=en-IN |date=25 March 2018}}</ref> Originally written in [[Malayalam]], the book was translated to English in 2007 by [[J. Devika]],<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/07/world/asia/07iht-letter.html|title=Giving a Voice to the Voiceless in India|journal=The New York Times|last=Roy|first=Nilanjana S.|date=2010-07-06|accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref> and into French the following year by Sophie Bastide-Foltz.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jameela |first1=Nalini |title=Autobiographie d'une travailleuse du sexe |date=2008 |publisher=Actes Sud |isbn=9782742775163 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=uCJBOAAACAAJ&dq=nalini+jameela |language=fr |translator-first1=Sophie |translator-last1=Bastide-Foltz}}</ref> The book created massive movements in society,<ref name=\"malayalam.webdunia\">{{cite web |title= \u0d1e\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d4d\u200d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d4b\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d02 \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02 \u0d2a\u0d4b\u0d30: \u0d28\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d3f \u0d1c\u0d2e\u0d40\u0d32 |trans-title=Don't just give us condoms, give us life: Nalini |url=http://malayalam.webdunia.com/article/kerala-news-in-malayalam/%E0%B4%9E%E0%B4%99%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%99%E0%B4%B3%E0%B5%8D%E2%80%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D-%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8B%E0%B4%A3%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%9F%E0%B4%82-%E0%B4%AE%E0%B4%BE%E0%B4%A4%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%B0%E0%B4%82-%E0%B4%AA%E0%B5%8B%E0%B4%B0-%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF-%E0%B4%9C%E0%B4%AE%E0%B5%80%E0%B4%B2-111061300008_1.htm |website=malayalam.webdunia.com |accessdate=10 March 2019|language=ml}}</ref> and led to many debates and controversies in Kerala.<ref name=\"actress\" /> The book was condemned by [[feminists]], who claimed it glorified sex work, and by conservatives who thought the subject should not be publicised.<ref name=\"chinadaily\" />\n\n===Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker===\nIn 2018 Jameela's second book ''Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sex-worker-nalini-jameela-pens-her-second-book/1/143701.html|title='Proud' sex worker Nalini Jameela pens her second book|last=Nair|first=Preetha S.|date=2011-07-05|publisher=[[India Today]]|accessdate=27 October 2011}}</ref> was published. The book was translated into English by Reshma Bharadwaj,<ref name=\"Scroll.in\" /> and also translated into [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Tamil language|Tamil]].<ref name=\"actress\" /> The book includes eight stories from the 1970s to the 2000s,<ref name=\"Firstpost\" /> telling of the relationships she developed with her clients.<ref name=\"The Indian Express\" />\n\n==Documentary==\nSanjeev Sivan, younger brother of noted film director [[Santosh Sivan]], made a 28-minute documentary film, ''Sex, Lies and a Book'', in 2013 about the life Jameela. The documentary was a joint venture of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP) and the [[Public Service Broadcasting Trust]]. Jameela appeared in the film.<ref name=\"actress\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jameela, Nalini}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in India]]\n[[Category:Female sex workers]]\n[[Category:Activists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Indian women social workers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women activists]]\n[[Category:Indian women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Thrissur]]\n[[Category:Indian women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Indian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Indian social sciences writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Indian female prostitutes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian writer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| image         = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| alt           = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1954|08|18}}  \n| birth_place   = [[Kallur, Thrissur|Kallur village]], [[Thrissur]], [[India]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Indian\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Prostitute]]<br>[[Sex work]] archivist<br>Author\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = Autobiography of a Sex Worker (2005)<br>Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker (2018)\n}}\n'''Nalini Jameela''' (born 18 August 1954) is an [[India]]n best selling author,<ref name=\"chinadaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-12/20/content_504790.htm|title=Indian prostitute mum sparks storm with book|date=2005-12-20|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn}}</ref> [[sex worker]] activist and former [[prostitute]] from [[Thrissur]], [[Kerala]]. She is the author of the books ''The Autobiography of a Sex-worker'' (2005) and ''Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker'' (2018). She is the coordinator of the ''Sex Workers Forum of Kerala'' (SWFK)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp|title=The life of the Silenced|last=Ittyipe|first=Minu S.|date=2005-07-30|publisher=[[Tehelka]]|accessdate=23 October 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130203204951/http://archive.tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp|archivedate=3 February 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and is a member of the five [[NGO|non-governmental organisations]] (NGO).<ref name=\"actress\" />\n\n==Biography==\nNalini Jameela was born on 18 August 1954 in [[Kallur, Thrissur|Kallur village]], [[Thrissur]], India. She worked in the fields planting and harvesting crops <ref name=\"Scroll.in\">{{cite web |last1=Jameela |first1=Nalini |title=In a new book, Nalini Jameela breaks taboos and writes about her romantic encounters as a sex worker |url=https://scroll.in/article/878956/in-a-new-book-nalini-jameela-breaks-taboos-and-writes-about-her-romantic-encounters-as-a-sex-worker |website=Scroll.in |accessdate=10 March 2019 |date=16 May 2018}}</ref> until her husband died of [[cancer]] when she was aged 24.<ref name=\"scmp\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/article/509522/indian-prostitute-reveals-all-gripping-autobiography|title=Indian prostitute reveals all in gripping autobiography|last=|first=|date=25 July 2005|work=South China Morning Post|access-date=2018-05-16|language=en}}</ref> This left her with no means of supporting her two young children.<ref name=\"Tehelka\">{{cite web |last1=Ittyipe |first1=Minu |title=The life of the Silenced |url=http://tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp |website=Tehelka - The People's Paper |accessdate=10 March 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314112521/http://tehelka.com/story_main13.asp?filename=hub073005the_life_of.asp |archivedate=14 March 2012 |date=14 March 2012}}</ref> A prostitute<ref name=\"scmp\" /> named Rosechechi introduced her to [[prostitution]]. Rosechechi arranged her first [[Client (prostitution)|client]], a senior police officer, and she met him in a guesthouse in Trissur that was frequented by politicians. When leaving the guesthouse in the morning she was arrested by the police and beaten.<ref name=\"Tehelka\" />\n\nShe had left school after the 3rd grade when she was about seven.<ref name=\"chinadaily\" /> In the 1990s she furthered her education at the Kallur Government School, eventually reaching the 12th grade.<ref name=\"puzha\" /> \n\nIn 2001 she became coordinator of the ''Sex Workers Forum of Kerala'' (SWFK),<ref name=\"puzha\">{{cite web |title=books.puzha.com - Author Details |url=http://www.puzha.com/malayalam/bookstore/cgi-bin/author-detail.cgi?code=2041 |website=www.puzha.com |accessdate=10 March 2019}}</ref> Under her leadership the SWFK held protest marches to draw attention to the plight of [[Street prostitution|street-based]] sex workers.<ref name=\"Firstpost\">{{cite web |last1=Mitra |first1=Ipshita |title=Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker: Nalini Jameela returns, with eight new stories from her past |url=https://www.firstpost.com/living/romantic-encounters-of-a-sex-worker-nalini-jameela-returns-with-eight-new-stories-from-her-past-4433545.html |website=Firstpost |accessdate=10 March 2019 |date=18 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nJameela is a member of the five non-governmental organisations (NGO).<ref name=\"actress\">{{cite web |title=\u0d28\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d3f \u0d1c\u0d2e\u0d40\u0d32\u0d2f\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d06\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d15\u0d25 \u0d05\u0d2d\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d2a\u0d3e\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d |trans-title=Nalini Jameela's autobiography |url=https://malayalam.boldsky.com/insync/2006/102606jameela-now-an-actress.html |website=malayalam.boldsky.com |accessdate=10 March 2019 |language=ml |date=26 October 2006}}</ref> At the fourth meeting of the AIDS Counselling Program in [[Bangalore]], she called on the government not just to distribute [[condoms]], but to provide an education to sex workers and their children.<ref name=\"malayalam.webdunia\" />\n\n==Works==\n===Autobiography of a Sex Worker===\nIn 2005 Jameela wrote the autobiographical book ''Oru Lymgikathozhilaliyude Atmakatha''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jameela |first1=Nalini |title=Oru Lymgikathozhilaliyude Atmakatha |date=2010 |publisher=D C Books |isbn=9788126438105 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=aemvDQAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=nalini+jameela#v=onepage&q=nalini%20jameela&f=false |language=ml |orig-year= 2005}}</ref> (Autobiography of a Sex Worker) with the aid of sex work activist I. Gopinath.<ref name=\"chinadaily\" /> The book sold 13,000 copies, ran to six editions within 100 days of publication.<ref name=\"The Indian Express\">{{cite web |last1=Pillai |first1=Pooja |title=How to Talk about Sex Without Offending People |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/express-sunday-eye/how-to-talk-about-sex-without-offending-people-5110176/ |website=The Indian Express |accessdate=10 March 2019 |language=en-IN |date=25 March 2018}}</ref> Originally written in [[Malayalam]], the book was translated to English in 2007 by [[J. Devika]],<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/07/world/asia/07iht-letter.html|title=Giving a Voice to the Voiceless in India|journal=The New York Times|last=Roy|first=Nilanjana S.|date=2010-07-06|accessdate=14 June 2011}}</ref> and into French the following year by Sophie Bastide-Foltz.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Jameela |first1=Nalini |title=Autobiographie d'une travailleuse du sexe |date=2008 |publisher=Actes Sud |isbn=9782742775163 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=uCJBOAAACAAJ&dq=nalini+jameela |language=fr |translator-first1=Sophie |translator-last1=Bastide-Foltz}}</ref> The book created massive movements in society,<ref name=\"malayalam.webdunia\">{{cite web |title= \u0d1e\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d4d\u200d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d4b\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d02 \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d02 \u0d2a\u0d4b\u0d30: \u0d28\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d3f \u0d1c\u0d2e\u0d40\u0d32 |trans-title=Don't just give us condoms, give us life: Nalini |url=http://malayalam.webdunia.com/article/kerala-news-in-malayalam/%E0%B4%9E%E0%B4%99%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%99%E0%B4%B3%E0%B5%8D%E2%80%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D-%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8B%E0%B4%A3%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%9F%E0%B4%82-%E0%B4%AE%E0%B4%BE%E0%B4%A4%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%B0%E0%B4%82-%E0%B4%AA%E0%B5%8B%E0%B4%B0-%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF-%E0%B4%9C%E0%B4%AE%E0%B5%80%E0%B4%B2-111061300008_1.htm |website=malayalam.webdunia.com |accessdate=10 March 2019|language=ml}}</ref> and led to many debates and controversies in Kerala.<ref name=\"actress\" /> The book was condemned by [[feminists]], who claimed it glorified sex work, and by conservatives who thought the subject should not be publicised.<ref name=\"chinadaily\" />\n\n===Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker===\nIn 2018 Jameela's second book ''Romantic Encounters of a Sex Worker''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/sex-worker-nalini-jameela-pens-her-second-book/1/143701.html|title='Proud' sex worker Nalini Jameela pens her second book|last=Nair|first=Preetha S.|date=2011-07-05|publisher=[[India Today]]|accessdate=27 October 2011}}</ref> was published. The book was translated into English by Reshma Bharadwaj,<ref name=\"Scroll.in\" /> and also translated into [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], [[Bengali language|Bengali]] and [[Tamil language|Tamil]].<ref name=\"actress\" /> The book includes eight stories from the 1970s to the 2000s,<ref name=\"Firstpost\" /> telling of the relationships she developed with her clients.<ref name=\"The Indian Express\" />\n\n==Documentary==\nSanjeev Sivan, younger brother of noted film director [[Santosh Sivan]], made a 28 minute documentary film, ''Sex, Lies and a Book'', in 2013 about the life Jameela. The documentary was a joint venture of the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP) and the [[Public Service Broadcasting Trust]]. Jameela appeared in the film.<ref name=\"actress\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jameela, Nalini}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women writers from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Sex worker activists in India]]\n[[Category:Female sex workers]]\n[[Category:Activists from Kerala]]\n[[Category:Indian women social workers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian women writers]]\n[[Category:Indian women activists]]\n[[Category:Indian women's rights activists]]\n[[Category:Writers from Thrissur]]\n[[Category:Indian women autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Indian autobiographers]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Indian social sciences writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Indian female prostitutes]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDocumentary:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 28 minute \u2192 28-minute", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nalini_Jameela"}
{"title_page": "List of hardware and software that supports FLAC", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\nThis is a list of [[computer hardware]] and [[software]] which supports [[FLAC]] (Free Lossless Audio Codec), a [[file format]] designed for [[lossless compression]] of [[digital audio]].\n\n== Hardware support ==\n\n=== Car devices ===\n\n* Alpine CDE-163BT\n* Alpine UTE-62BT\n* [[Citro\u00ebn]] DS5\n* [[Hyundai Ioniq]]\n* Hyundai Kona\n* Kenwood KMM-100U\n* [[Peugeot]] 208 Blue Lion\n* Pioneer Avic-4100 -> 8100NEX\n* Pioneer DEH-X8700BH\n* Power Acoustik PD-622NB\n* [[Renault Espace]]\n* [[SEAT Le\u00f3n]]\n* Sony MEX-N5100BT\n* Sony MEX-XB100BT\n* Tesla Models 3, S & X\n\n=== DJ players ===\n\n*[[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer]] CDJ-2000nexus2<ref>http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/cdj-2000nxs2/black/specifications/</ref>\n*[[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer]] CDJ-TOUR1<ref>http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/cdj-tour1/black/specifications/</ref>\n*[[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer]] XDJ-1000mk2<ref>http://www.pioneerdj.com/en/product/player/xdj-1000mk2/black/specifications/</ref>\n\n=== Portable stereo / boombox ===\n\n=== Active speakers ===\n\n* [http://en.fenda.com/index.php/Home/Article/detail/id/115.html Fenda] F&D A140X, [https://www.gizguide.com/2017/07/fd-a180x-review.html F&D A180X]\n\n=== Home audio AV receivers / amplifiers ===\n\n* [[Bang and Olufsen]] BeoSound 5 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bang-olufsen.com/en-US/sound/sound-systems/beosound-5/ |title= Bang and Olufsen BeoSound 5 |accessdate=6 April 2013}}</ref>\n*[[Denon]] AVP-A1HDCI, AVR-4810, AVR-4310,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denon.co.uk/uk/product/pages/product-detail.aspx?catid=hometheatre&subid=avreceivers&productid=avr4310|title=DENON UK \u2013 AVR-4310|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref> AVR-4311, AVR-3310, AVR-5308, AVR-4308, AVR-3808, AVR-X1000,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denon.co.uk/uk/product/pages/product-detail.aspx?catid=hometheatre&subid=avreceivers&productid=avrx1000|title=DENON UK - AVR-X1000|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref> AVR-X2000, AVR-X3000, AVR-X4000, AVR-4520, DNP-720AE<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.denon.co.uk/uk/product/pages/product-detail.aspx?catid=networkproducts&subid=networkaudioplayer&productid=dnp720ae|title=DENON UK \u2013 Network Audio Player with AirPlay|accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Escient]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.escient.com/support/supportdocuments/DigitalMusicFilesFormats.pdf |title=Supported Digital Music Formats & Tagging Requirements |accessdate=27 January 2008 |format=PDF |publisher=Escient |page=2}}</ref>\n*[[Onkyo]] TX-SR333, TX-NR535, TX-NR626, TX-NR636, TX-NR737, TX-NR838, TX-NR1030, TX-NR3030\n*[[Pioneer Corporation|Pioneer]] SC-05, SC-07, SC-25, SC-27, SC-35, SC-37, SC-09TX, X-HM76B, XC-HM86\n*[[Sonos]] 16-bit max.\n* [[Sony]]'s High-Res Audio Players<ref>{{cite web |url=http://discover.store.sony.com/High-Resolution-Audio/ |title=Sony High-Resolution Audio products page |accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Yamaha]] RX-A1000/A2000/A3000 AV Receiver, [https://europe.yamaha.com/en/products/audio_visual/av_receivers_amps/rx-v477/index.html RX-V477], RX-V671, RX-V673 (RX-V773, RX-V671, RX-V673 - up to 96 kHz streaming and 192 kHz external link) AV Receivers, RX-V773, RX-V795, RX-V1067, RX-V2065 AV Receiver, RX-V2067, RX-V3067 AV Receivers\n\n=== Home media servers and clients ===\n\n* [[Cambridge Audio]] CXN Network Player | Azur 851N Network Player\n* Dvico TVIX HD M-6500, N1 (cafe), HD M-6600A/N Plus, HD M-7000\n*[[Linn Products|Linn]] Klimax DS, Renew DS, Akurate DS, Majik DS and Sneaky Music DS\n*Logitech [[Squeezebox network music player|Squeezebox and Transporter]] network music players from [[Logitech]].  Current products decode natively, old v1 units transcode to [[Pulse-code modulation|PCM]] on the server. (discontinued)\n*[[Naim Audio]] HDX Hard Disk Player,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.naim-audio.com/products/hdx.html|title=Naim Audio HDX}}</ref> NaimUniti, UnitiQute, DAC, NDX, UnitiServe\n*[[Meridian Audio, Ltd.|Meridian Sooloos]]\n*Pixel Magic Systems' HD Mediabox (with firmware 1.3.4 or higher)\n*[[PS Audio]] Perfect Wave DAC + Bridge (Digital-to-Analog Converter/Digital Streamer)\n*[[Seagate FreeAgent]] Theater+ HD, HDTV Network Media Player STAJ100\n*T+A Music Player<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.taelektroakustik.de/eng/ta2/e_system/music_player.htm |title=T+A E-Series Music-Player |accessdate=27 January 2008}}</ref>\n*Western Digital [[WD TV]] HD based\n\n=== Portable handheld players ===\n\n*Colorfly C3, C4, C10, C200\n*Creative Zen X-Fi 2\n* [[FiiO X Series]]\n*[[iAudio]] ([[Cowon]]): A2, A3, 6, 7, F2, O2, M3, M5, X5, U3, U5,<ref>[[H.264-HD Encoder Core]]\n</ref> D2, D2+, S9, J3, X7 native support with newer firmware.\n*[[iriver]] E200, E150, [[iriver E100|E100]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iriver.com.au/iriver/index.cfm?pageID=2&sID=1&prodID=23&# |title=iRiver E100}}</ref>  E50, E30, Lplayer, SPINN, T8.\n*Meizu [[M6 Mini Player]], M3 Music Card\n*[[PonoPlayer]]\n*[[Rio Karma]]\n*Samsung YP-U5<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.samsung.com/us/consumer/mobile/mp3-players/mp3-players/YP-U5JQB/XAA/index.idx?pagetype=prd_detail&tab=spec |title=Samsung |accessdate=8 October 2009}}</ref> USB stick portable player\n* Sandisk Clip Sport\n*[[SanDisk Sansa]] [[Sansa Fuze|Fuze]], Clip (with updated firmware),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.engadget.com/2008/10/04/sansa-fuze-updated-to-support-ogg-and-flac/ |title=Sansa Fuze updated to support Ogg and FLAC |accessdate=18 October 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anythingbutipod.com/archives/2008/10/sansa-clip-firmware-010130-released.php |title=Sansa Clip Firmware 01.01.30 Released |accessdate=18 October 2008}}</ref> Clip+,<ref>anythingbutipod.com: [http://www.anythingbutipod.com/archives/2009/08/sandisk-sansa-clip-plus-review.php SanDisk Sansa Clip+ Plus Review]</ref> Fuze+, Clip Zip\n*Teclast T29, T39, C260, C280, C290\n* TRAXMOD Open source, open hardware portable MMC/SD player\n*[[Trekstor Vibez]]\n*VEDIA A10, B6\n\n=== Smartphones and tablets ===\n\n*Archos 5 Internet Tablet\n*Archos Internet Media Tablets<ref>{{cite web|url=http://update.archos.com/6/archos5-7/changes_firmware_archos5-7.html |title=Archos 5 and Archos 7&nbsp;\u2013 Firmware Changes |publisher=Update.archos.com |date= |accessdate=24 March 2009}}</ref>\n*[[Nokia N900]], [[Nokia N9]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conversations.nokia.com/2011/07/07/nokia-n9-pure-entertainment/ |title=N9 |accessdate=16 January 2012}}</ref>\n* [[BlackBerry Playbook]] Tablet, [[BlackBerry 10]] smartphones\n*Most Android devices with a compatible third-party player, such as Apollo or {{cite web |url=https://wiki.videolan.org/FLAC/ |title=VLC |accessdate=22 February 2016}}\n**[[Samsung]] [[Samsung Droid Charge|Droid Charge]], [[Samsung Epic 4G|Galaxy S II Epic 4G Touch]], [[Samsung Exhibit 4G|Exhibit 4G]], [[Samsung Fascinate|Fascinate]], [[Samsung Infuse 4G|Infuse 4G]], [[Samsung Mesmerize|Mesmerize]]<ref name=\"GSM Arena\" />\n**[[Samsung Galaxy Note (original)|Samsung Galaxy Note]], [[Samsung Galaxy R|R]], [[Samsung Galaxy S|S]], [[Samsung Galaxy S Plus|S Plus]], [[Samsung Galaxy S II|S II]], [[Samsung Galaxy S II LTE|S II LTE]], [[Samsung Galaxy S III|S III]], [[Samsung Galaxy W]], [[Samsung Galaxy SL|SL]], [[Samsung Galaxy Tab|Tab]], [[Samsung Galaxy U|U]]<ref name=\"GSM Arena\" /> and all later models running Android 3.1 or later\n**[[LG Optimus G]], [[LG G2]], [[LG G3]], [[LG G4]], [[LG V10]], [[LG G5]], [[LG V20]]\n**Sony Xperia Z series, Sony Xperia X, XA, XA1\n*[[Samsung Wave]] series\n* Windows Mobile 6.5 or earlier with compatible third-party software player.\n* Windows Phone devices running Windows 10 Mobile (Windows Phone 7/8 may vary).\n* [[Jolla (smartphone)|Jolla]] series of smartphones\n\n=== Blu-ray / DVD / USB players ===\n* LG UBKM9, UBK90, UBK80 (Blu-ray players with USB port)\n* [[OPPO Digital]] BDP-93 & BDP-95 and BDP-103 & BDP-105 Universal Network 3D Blu-ray Disc Players, and UDP-203 & UDP-205 4K Ultra HD Blu-ray Disc Players\n* Panasonic BDP-BD77,BDT500<ref>http://www.whathifi.com/news/ces-2012-panasonic-blu-ray-players-feature-quality-dac-and-flac-support</ref>\n* [[Roku]] Ultra (media player)\n* Samsung HT-H4500R <ref>https://www.samsung.com/uk/audio-video/blu-ray-home-entertainement-system-h4500r</ref>\n* Sony BDP-S1200, BDP-S3200,BDP-S4200,BDP-S5200<ref>http://pdf.crse.com/manuals/4476203411.pdf</ref>\n\n=== Portable handheld recorders ===\n* Olympus LS-P4\n\n=== Unsorted ===\n\n* Embedded Waveplayer Module with FLAC level 0\u20132 support, MIDI and serial interface\n\n== Software support ==\n{{Example farm|section|date=November 2011}}\n\n=== Encoding ===\nAlthough some software supports FLAC natively \"out of the box\", some require installation of a third-part FLAC filter or plug-in. \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 85%; text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width: 25%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Name\n! style=\"width: 40%;\" rowspan=\"2\" | Description\n! style=\"width: 35%;\" colspan=\"3\" | Platform\n|-\n! Windows\n! Mac OS X\n! GNU/Linux\n|-\n| [[Adobe Audition]]\n| Does not natively support FLAC but can use a third-party filter. \n| {{yes}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vuplayer.com/audition.php |title=Cool Edit / Adobe Audition file filters|author=vuplayer.com |date= |accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref>\n| {{No}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n| [[aTunes]]\n|\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{No}}\n|-\n| [[ALLPlayer]]\n|\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|-\n| [[Audacious (software)|Audacious]]\n|\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n|-\n| [[Audacity (audio editor)|Audacity]]\n| Possible since version 1.2.5.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://audacity.sourceforge.net/about/news?id=2006-10-30/1.3.2-release&lang=en |title=Audacity 1.3.2 a 1.2.5 released |author=Audacity development team |date=2006-10-30 |accessdate=19 January 2010}}</ref>\nFull support since 2.0.0<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wiki.a