ory:Lotte Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Films about comfort women]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Virginia]]\n[[Category:World War II war crimes trials films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I_Can_Speak"}
{"title_page": "Russ Cohen", "text_new": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Russ Cohen\n| image = Russ Cohen - UC.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Cohen pictured in ''The Cincinnatian 1937'', Cincinnati yearbook\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1893|2|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Augusta, Georgia]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1981|4|7|1893|2|13}}\n| death_place = [[Waynesboro, Georgia]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1913\u20131916\n| player_team1 = [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]]\n| player_positions = [[End (gridiron football)|End]]\n| coach_years1 = 1923\u20131926\n| coach_team1 = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1928\u20131931\n| coach_team2 = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| coach_years3 = 1932\n| coach_team3 = [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 1935\u20131937\n| coach_team4 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| admin_years1 = 1928\u20131931\n| admin_team1 = [[LSU Tigers|LSU]]\n| overall_record = 31\u201325\u20134\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] (1915)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Henry Russell Cohen''' (February 13, 1893 \u2013 April 7, 1981) was an [[American football]] player, coach, and college athletics administrator.<ref>http://www.thetruecitizen.com/news/2015-10-28/Front_Page/Russ_Cohen__the_pointaminute_team.html</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nCohen played as a prominent [[End (gridiron football)|end]] for [[Dan McGugin]]'s [[Vanderbilt Commodores football]] teams, serving as [[Captain (sports)|captain]] of its \"point-a-minute\" [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (SIAA) champion [[1915 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|1915 team]], with the likes of [[Josh Cody]] and [[Irby Curry]]. Cohen was selected [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] the same year.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper = Atlanta Constitution|title = Composite All-Southern Of Ten Of The Dopesters|author = [[Dick Jemison]]|date = November 30, 1915}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nCohen scouted teams for [[Wallace Wade]] at [[University of Alabama|Alabama]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5359558/the_waco_newstribune/|work=The Waco News-Tribune|title=Who's Who Among Grid Leaders|date=October 11, 1928|page=8|accessdate=May 23, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> He was the head football coach at [[Louisiana State University]] (LSU) from 1928 to 1931<ref>{{cite web| title=LSU Football media guide|publisher=lsusports.net| url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=27815&SPID=2164&DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=205502494|accessdate=October 25, 2013}}</ref> and at the [[University of Cincinnati]] from 1935 to 1937, compiling a career record of 31\u201325\u20134.\n===LSU===\nAs was tradition for football coaches at the time, he also served as the [[athletics director]] at LSU during his tenure as head football coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lsusports.net/fls/5200/assets/docs/fb/pdf/17guide.pdf|title=LSU Year-by-Year Records|publisher=lsusports.net|page=107|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> His record with the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]] was 23\u201313\u20131. Coach McGugin recommended Cohen for the LSU job.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/fottballsgreates00pope#page/340/mode/2up|title=Football's Greatest Coaches|page=341|author=[[Edwin Pope]]|via=[[archive.org]]|accessdate=March 8, 2015|year=1955}} {{Open access}}</ref> [[Huey P. Long]] was an ardent supporter of the team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5465325/cumberland_evening_times/|page=12|date=December 4, 1930|title=Huey P. Long Startling As A Football Fan|work=Cumberland Evening Times|accessdate=June 2, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> \n\nCohen's best year at LSU was probably his first, in [[1928 LSU Tigers football team|1928]]. Led by All-Southern captain [[Jess Tinsley]], the Tigers posted a 6\u20132\u20131 record, suffering losses to [[1928 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] and Wade's [[1928 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]. Star halfback Percy Brown broke his shoulder against Alabama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/schools/alab/graphics/docs/28-m-footbl-recap.pdf|title=1928 Season|publisher=grfx.cstv.com|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> The tie was to [[Bill Banker]] and rival [[1928 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]], which was as good as its ever been from 1929 to 1931.  In [[1931 LSU Tigers football team|1931]] LSU played its first night game in [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Tiger Stadium]], a 31\u20130 victory over [[Spring Hill Badgers football|Spring Hill]].\n\n===Cincinnati===\nWith the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati Bearcats]], he compiled an 8\u201312\u20133 mark.<ref>{{cite web| title=Russell T. \"Russ\" Cohen Records by Year|publisher=cfbdatawarehouse.com/| url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=410|accessdate=October 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]]\n | conf      = [[Southern Conference]]\n | startyear = 1928\n | endyear   = 1931\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1928 college football season|1928]]\n | name         = [[1928 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n | overall      = 6\u20132\u20131\n | conference   = 3\u20131\u20131\n | confstanding = 6th\n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1929 college football season|1929]]\n | name         = [[1929 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n | overall      = 6\u20133\n | conference   = 3\u20132\n | confstanding = 10th\n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1930 college football season|1930]]\n | name         = [[1930 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n | overall      = 6\u20134\n | conference   = 2\u20134\n | confstanding = 16th\n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1931 college football season|1931]]\n | name         = [[1931 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n | overall      = 5\u20134\n | conference   = 3\u20132\n | confstanding = 7th\n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = LSU\n | overall    = 23\u201313\u20131\n | confrecord = 11\u20139\u20131\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati Bearcats]]\n | conf      = [[Buckeye Athletic Association]]\n | startyear = 1935\n | endyear   = 1937\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1935 college football season|1935]]\n | name         = [[1935 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]]\n | overall      = 7\u20132\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1936 college football season|1936]]\n | name         = [[1936 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]]\n | overall      = 1\u20135\u20133\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1937 college football season|1937]]\n | name         = [[1937 Cincinnati Bearcats football team|Cincinnati]]\n | overall      = 0\u20135*\n | conference   = \n | confstanding = \n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subtotal\n | name       = Cincinnati\n | overall    = 8\u201312\u20133\n | confrecord = \n}}*<small>Last 5 games of season were coached by [[Wade Woodworth]].</small>\n{{CFB Yearly Record End\n | overall  = 31\u201325\u20134 \n | bowls    = no\n | poll     = no\n | polltype = \n | legend   = no\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{LSU Tigers athletic director navbox}}\n{{LSU Tigers football coach navbox}}\n{{Cincinnati Bearcats football coach navbox}}\n{{1925 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{1926 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{1915 College Football Composite All-Southerns}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Russ}}\n[[Category:1893 births]]\n[[Category:1981 deaths]]\n[[Category:American football ends]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football coaches]]\n[[Category:Cincinnati Bearcats football coaches]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers and Lady Tigers athletic directors]]\n[[Category:LSU Tigers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Vanderbilt Commodores football players]]\n[[Category:All-Southern college football players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Augusta, Georgia]]\n[[Category:People from Waynesboro, Georgia]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Russ Cohen\n| image = Russ Cohen - UC.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Cohen pictured in ''The Cincinnatian 1937'', Cincinnati yearbook\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1893|2|13}}\n| birth_place = [[Augusta, Georgia]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|1981|4|7|1893|2|13}}\n| death_place = [[Waynesboro, Georgia]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1913\u20131916\n| player_team1 = [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]]\n| player_positions = [[End (gridiron football)|End]]\n| coach_years1 = 1923\u20131926\n| coach_team1 = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1928\u20131931\n| coach_team2 = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]]\n| coach_years3 = 1932\n| coach_team3 = [[Vanderbilt Commodores football|Vanderbilt]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 1935\u20131937\n| coach_team4 = [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati]]\n| admin_years1 = 1928\u20131931\n| admin_team1 = [[LSU Tigers|LSU]]\n| overall_record = 31\u201325\u20134\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] (1915)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Henry Russell Cohen''' (February 13, 1893 \u2013 April 7, 1981) was an [[American football]] player, coach, and college athletics administrator.<ref>http://www.thetruecitizen.com/news/2015-10-28/Front_Page/Russ_Cohen__the_pointaminute_team.html</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nCohen played as a prominent [[End (gridiron football)|end]] for [[Dan McGugin]]'s [[Vanderbilt Commodores football]] teams, serving as [[Captain (sports)|captain]] of its \"point-a-minute\" [[Southern Intercollegiate Athletic Association]] (SIAA) champion [[1915 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|1915 team]], with the likes of [[Josh Cody]] and [[Irby Curry]]. Cohen was selected [[College Football All-Southern Team|All-Southern]] the same year.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper = Atlanta Constitution|title = Composite All-Southern Of Ten Of The Dopesters|author = [[Dick Jemison]]|date = November 30, 1915}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nCohen scouted teams for [[Wallace Wade]] at [[University of Alabama|Alabama]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5359558/the_waco_newstribune/|work=The Waco News-Tribune|title=Who's Who Among Grid Leaders|date=October 11, 1928|page=8|accessdate=May 23, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> He was the head football coach at [[Louisiana State University]] (LSU) from 1928 to 1931<ref>{{cite web| title=LSU Football media guide|publisher=lsusports.net| url=http://www.lsusports.net/ViewArticle.dbml?SPSID=27815&SPID=2164&DB_OEM_ID=5200&ATCLID=205502494|accessdate=October 25, 2013}}</ref> and at the [[University of Cincinnati]] from 1935 to 1937, compiling a career record of 31\u201325\u20134.\n===LSU===\nAs was tradition for football coaches at the time, he also served as the [[athletics director]] at LSU during his tenure as head football coach.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lsusports.net/fls/5200/assets/docs/fb/pdf/17guide.pdf|title=LSU Year-by-Year Records|publisher=lsusports.net|page=107|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> His record with the [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]] was 23\u201313\u20131. Coach McGugin recommended Cohen for the LSU job.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/stream/fottballsgreates00pope#page/340/mode/2up|title=Football's Greatest Coaches|page=341|author=[[Edwin Pope]]|via=[[archive.org]]|accessdate=March 8, 2015|year=1955}} {{Open access}}</ref> [[Huey P. Long]] was an ardent supporter of the team.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/5465325/cumberland_evening_times/|page=12|date=December 4, 1930|title=Huey P. Long Startling As A Football Fan|work=Cumberland Evening Times|accessdate=June 2, 2016|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}} {{Open access}}</ref> \n\nCohen's best year at LSU was probably his first, in [[1928 LSU Tigers football team|1928]]. Led by All-Southern captain [[Jess Tinsley]], the Tigers posted a 6\u20132\u20131 record, suffering losses to [[1928 Arkansas Razorbacks football team|Arkansas]] and Wade's [[1928 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]. Star halfback Percy Brown broke his shoulder against Alabama.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grfx.cstv.com/schools/alab/graphics/docs/28-m-footbl-recap.pdf|title=1928 Season|publisher=grfx.cstv.com|accessdate=July 29, 2018}}</ref> The tie was to [[Bill Banker]] and rival [[1928 Tulane Green Wave football team|Tulane]], which was as good as its ever been from 1929 to 1931.  In [[1931 LSU Tigers football team|1931]] LSU played its first night game in [[Tiger Stadium (LSU)|Tiger Stadium]], a 31\u20130 victory over [[Spring Hill Badgers football|Spring Hill]].\n\n===Cincinnati===\nWith the [[Cincinnati Bearcats football|Cincinnati Bearcats]], he compiled an 8\u201312\u20133 mark.<ref>{{cite web| title=Russell T. \"Russ\" Cohen Records by Year|publisher=cfbdatawarehouse.com/| url=http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_year_by_year.php?coachid=410|accessdate=October 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU Tigers]]\n | conf      = [[Southern Conference]]\n | startyear = 1928\n | endyear   = 1931\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1928 college football season|1928]]\n | name         = [[1928 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n | overall      = 6\u20132\u20131\n | conference   = 3\u20131\u20131\n | confstanding = 6th\n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1929 college football season|1929]]\n | name         = [[1929 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n | overall      = 6\u20133\n | conference   = 3\u20132\n | confstanding = 10th\n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no\n | ranking2     = no\n}}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Entry\n | championship = \n | year         = [[1930 college football season|1930]]\n | name         = [[1930 LSU Tigers football team|LSU]]\n | overall      = 6\u20134\n | conference   = 2\u20134\n | confstanding = 16th\n | bowl         = \n | bowlname     = \n | bowloutcome  = \n | bcsbowl      = \n | ranking      = no